</b>): from the Biblical personal name <i>Šavel</i>, Hebrew <i>Shaul</i> (see   Saul  ). It may be a nickname for a godless person, from the archaic word <i>šavel</i>, which is derived from the Biblical name.","Slovenian (<b>Šavel</b>): probably from an old spelling of the Biblical personal name <i>Savel</i> (see   Saul  , compare 2 above). Alternatively, perhaps a nickname or a topographic name from an old vernacular spelling of the same plant name as in 4 below.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Šavelj</b>: probably a nickname or a topographic name from the plant name <i>š(č)avelj</i> ‘sorrel (Rumex acetosa)’."]},{"name":"Savelle","meanings":["English: variant of   Saville  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Savell","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Saville  ."]},{"name":"Seville","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Saville  ."]},{"name":"Saffell","meanings":["English (Essex): from the Middle English personal name <i>Safugel</i> (Old Norse <i>sǽfogl</i> ‘sea-bird, especially the cormorant’), not recorded as a personal name in Scandinavia, but common in England after the Norman Conquest. In some cases with voicing of intervocalic /f/ to /v/, there may have been confusion with   Saville  ."]}]},{"name":"Avice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Aveza</i>, derived from a short form of one or more compound names containing the first element <i>av</i> (as in   Ava ;  the meaning is uncertain). The correspondence in form to the Latin word <i>avis</i> ‘bird’ is coincidental."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Avice de Saville was born about 1218, in Sevilla, Andalusia, Spain, her father, Henry de Savile, was 10 and her mother, Mrs. Henry de Savile, was 60. She had at least 1 son with Hugh Pincerna Botiler of Sandal."},"et":{"about 1218–":"umbes 1218–Surnud","1218–Female":"1218–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","about 1218":"umbes 1218","1233":"1233","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1233":"umbes 1233","1160":"1160","1218":"1218","Sevilla, Andalusia, Spain":"Sevilla, Andalucía, Hispaania","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1218–":"noin 1218–Kuollut","1218–Female":"1218–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut